ls3.sh

This script lists only the files ending in .html in the directory you are currently in.
Bash

#!/bin/bash
ls *.html

ls4.sh

This script lists .html files located in the sub-directories of your current directory. (This matches the wildcard pattern used in your previous Shakespeare exercises).
Bash

#!/bin/bash
ls */*.html

dr.sh

The -r flag reverses the standard alphabetical sorting order of the ls command.
Bash

#!/bin/bash
ls -r

du2.sh

This calculates the disk usage (du) for items in the current directory, summarizing them (-s), displaying in kilobytes (-k), and then piping that output into sort to order them numerically (-n) by size.
Bash

#!/bin/bash
du -sk * | sort -n or just du | sort -n

(Note: If the Einstein test strictly wants ONLY sub-directories and no individual files, use du -sk */ | sort -n instead).
grep2.sh

This searches for the exact lowercase string "queen". Remember that grep is case-sensitive by default. As requested, the target file is set to macbeth.htm for the upload.
Bash

#!/bin/bash
grep "queen" macbeth.htm

grep3.sh

To ignore case and find "Queen", "QUEEN", or "queen", you add the -i (ignore case) switch.
Bash

#!/bin/bash
grep -i "queen" macbeth.htm
